51
00:03:10,448 --> 00:03:17,955
So, you know, one of our big conclusions is that virtual reality is still really best experienced and shown in person, right?

52
00:03:18,856 --> 00:03:22,379
It's not just one person at home playing a game alone.

53
00:03:22,399 --> 00:03:27,424
A lot of people have their first, their very first virtual reality experiences out in public.

54
00:03:27,464 --> 00:03:28,725
It could be at an event like this.

55
00:03:28,765 --> 00:03:30,506
It could be a showcase, an arcade.

56
00:03:31,607 --> 00:03:34,969
And you know, my complaint and beef there is that VR is just still too expensive.

57
00:03:35,069 --> 00:03:35,810
And people come up to me and say,

58
00:03:35,830 --> 00:03:38,672
Hey Patrick, virtual reality sounds awesome. How do I get into it?

59
00:03:39,072 --> 00:03:43,755
There's like a half hour conversation about budgets and technologies and all of that about what to experience.

60
00:03:43,875 --> 00:03:47,658
Whereas I can just be like, hey, go to this place, do this virtual reality here at this event.

61
00:03:48,178 --> 00:03:52,461
And so all of us as an industry want that to be the best possible first experience.

62
00:03:52,521 --> 00:03:55,363
We don't want to turn people off from this medium, this technology, this industry.

63
00:03:55,803 --> 00:03:58,645
We want to invite as many people into it, both as, you know.

64
00:03:59,255 --> 00:04:01,759
Consumers, but more importantly, as creators and collaborators.

65
00:04:02,520 --> 00:04:05,165
And so we think that these live events are a best place to do it.

66
00:04:05,285 --> 00:04:08,771
It's a social experience, you can share photos, memories, and

67
00:04:08,791 --> 00:04:09,913
also just have a laugh with people.

68
00:04:09,933 --> 00:04:12,518
And that helps cement it as a positive experience with each other.

69
00:04:15,708 --> 00:04:19,413
Because it's such a far-reaching experience, you can no longer consider just one person,

70
00:04:19,473 --> 00:04:22,497
the player, at the end of the long development cycle, like,

71
00:04:22,617 --> 00:04:24,120
ah, yes, we must please this one person.

72
00:04:24,660 --> 00:04:28,466
You are thinking of multiple audiences, and you have to consider all of their needs, desires,

73
00:04:28,506 --> 00:04:30,248
and what shows well to them.

74
00:04:31,249 --> 00:04:35,653
So with a VR experience, your first concentric circle of the audience is the person who's playing it.

75
00:04:36,914 --> 00:04:40,197
The next one out, the next closest to that experience, are people who are standing in

76
00:04:40,217 --> 00:04:44,441
line. They've already opted into your experience, you've sold them, they're ready to wait and spend

77
00:04:44,461 --> 00:04:49,466
their time with you. Beyond that is the audience who's maybe walking past that line and then they

78
00:04:49,526 --> 00:04:53,329
see this long line and their interest is piqued and now they slow down and they're watching and

79
00:04:53,389 --> 00:04:54,851
you want to make sure that you have something.

80
00:04:55,311 --> 00:04:59,833
of interest for them. Beyond the in-person audience, they're live streamers. If people

81
00:04:59,853 --> 00:05:04,794
are walking around with their live stream camera going or they're digitally streaming a conference,

82
00:05:05,295 --> 00:05:08,656
you want to make sure that the content is accessible and attractive to those audiences.

83
00:05:09,056 --> 00:05:14,158
And then beyond that, even further, is the digital footprint of this experience on the internet.

84
00:05:14,638 --> 00:05:18,280
Blogs, write-ups, photo galleries, clips, GIFs.

85
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:20,760
You want to make sure that the things that you are putting out there

86
00:05:21,260 --> 00:05:24,141
are very easy for all of the basically amateur

87
00:05:25,202 --> 00:05:28,262
advertisements and photographers that all of the audience with a phone is.

88
00:05:28,383 --> 00:05:29,123
Like all of them.

89
00:05:29,263 --> 00:05:32,424
You want to make sure that it's easy for them to capture it and show off your best side.

90
00:05:33,064 --> 00:05:36,105
Our friend Wiley, who's put on Fantastic Arcade for many years,

91
00:05:36,565 --> 00:05:37,665
said something very astute. He said,

92
00:05:38,225 --> 00:05:39,646
if it's not on YouTube, it didn't happen.

93
00:05:40,255 --> 00:05:48,744
And so we kind of think about that as being one of the end products of this virtual reality experience is a 2D video of people doing it that lives on the internet forever.

94
00:05:50,656 --> 00:05:57,702
So with that in mind, there are these three sort of big facets of a show to design, and particularly the app that you're bringing to that show.

95
00:05:58,022 --> 00:06:03,066
The very first part is the virtual reality software. This is what is happening inside the headset to that person's brain.

96
00:06:03,627 --> 00:06:09,352
The second part is the physical space setup. This sort of straddles the inside-outside headset divide,

97
00:06:09,432 --> 00:06:13,695
because a lot of what your physical space is going to impact is going to change how that person can

98
00:06:13,735 --> 00:06:15,977
behave in the virtual reality experience or the...

99
00:06:16,542 --> 00:06:21,244
AR, XR, MR experience, and also how they're going to be impacted physically in the real world.

100
00:06:21,765 --> 00:06:24,786
And then the emotional experience happens primarily out of the headset.

101
00:06:24,886 --> 00:06:29,988
Once that person has waited in line and they've been set up to enjoy the experience afterwards,

102
00:06:30,108 --> 00:06:34,430
what is their emotional takeaway? Because that lasts so much longer than the facts of the experience.

103
00:06:36,531 --> 00:06:41,013
So first we'd like to talk about this notion of the virtual experience and how we design it.

104
00:06:42,611 --> 00:06:47,652
So just like how I'm a big believer that in-person experiences are some of the best ways to experience VR,

105
00:06:47,672 --> 00:06:52,874
the opposite side of that experience is that almost everyone is new to VR.

106
00:06:52,894 --> 00:06:56,115
The people who are going to come to an event or wait in line especially

107
00:06:56,355 --> 00:06:58,235
are the people who are most hungry for virtual reality.

108
00:06:58,255 --> 00:07:01,076
That often means that they have the least prior experience with it, right?

109
00:07:01,476 --> 00:07:04,817
If you're Daniel and you have six headsets at home, you're probably not going to wait in line.

110
00:07:06,078 --> 00:07:09,679
So we try to think about the absolute broadest experience we can

111
00:07:10,239 --> 00:07:11,399
and make sure that our experiences are.

112
00:07:11,659 --> 00:07:14,380
easy to use, and also easy to make look good.

113
00:07:14,740 --> 00:07:17,521
Because, you know, we're keeping in mind not just the player,

114
00:07:17,561 --> 00:07:19,142
but also everyone else watching them.

115
00:07:19,762 --> 00:07:21,563
And so we try to include ideas or mechanics

116
00:07:21,943 --> 00:07:23,343
that make it easy for them to have fun

117
00:07:23,623 --> 00:07:25,124
and also easy for them to show it off.

118
00:07:25,144 --> 00:07:27,765
Like, let's give them lots of guides and lots of helping hands

119
00:07:27,805 --> 00:07:29,005
within the VR experience

120
00:07:29,626 --> 00:07:31,506
so that they can show it off to other novices

121
00:07:31,566 --> 00:07:33,887
who are there at the event waiting to participate.

122
00:07:34,640 --> 00:07:39,024
Even if the player is not hitting your win case in the demo or the game itself, they

123
00:07:39,044 --> 00:07:42,987
should have fun while failing and still come back and be like, no, I want to wait in line

124
00:07:43,027 --> 00:07:43,748
again and I want to try.

125
00:07:43,768 --> 00:07:45,510
This time I figured out what I should be doing.

126
00:07:45,630 --> 00:07:48,132
Or like, hey, I totally just flailed around.

127
00:07:48,152 --> 00:07:51,355
I have no idea what I was supposed to be doing, but I had fun doing it.

128
00:07:51,395 --> 00:07:54,358
I'm going to tell my friends about how cool VR is, how cool this app is.

129
00:07:56,368 --> 00:08:00,970
So another way to make sure that you're going to be generating more and more good experiences

130
00:08:01,070 --> 00:08:02,991
from your showcase is to keep it short and sweet.

131
00:08:03,831 --> 00:08:08,233
We try to average less than 10 minutes, and that's not just time in the experience, that's

132
00:08:08,293 --> 00:08:11,454
including the getting people into VR and back out of it.

133
00:08:11,474 --> 00:08:14,896
So our turnaround times are between 7 and 8 minutes on show floors.

134
00:08:15,676 --> 00:08:20,160
The more physical your VR experience is, or your AR experience, your XR, all of the Rs,

135
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,221
the shorter your session should be.

136
00:08:22,341 --> 00:08:27,546
And that's because if you're out there and you're punching and fighting and jumping and dodging and all these things,

137
00:08:27,786 --> 00:08:30,708
at the end of it, your muscles are sore, you're sweaty, you're out of breath.

138
00:08:31,068 --> 00:08:34,591
You want to make sure that people are leaving your experience energized and hyped,

139
00:08:34,791 --> 00:08:39,415
and maybe a little bit out of breath, but you can go on and talk to your friends about how cool it was

140
00:08:39,475 --> 00:08:42,998
and not need to go sit down for half an hour and maybe miss the next cool thing that you wanted to see.

141
00:08:44,668 --> 00:08:48,269
Look for example to Beat Saber, where most of the songs are under or at three minutes.

142
00:08:48,629 --> 00:08:53,370
That's a pretty ideal cutoff point for something that's hyper, hyper physical.

143
00:08:53,930 --> 00:08:57,371
And another thing about shorter experiences is that the line keeps moving.

144
00:08:57,411 --> 00:09:00,752
So hopefully you have a long line full of eager people ready to play your experience,

145
00:09:01,152 --> 00:09:03,333
try your app, or even just see what it's about.

146
00:09:03,873 --> 00:09:06,373
The shorter the line, or the faster the line is moving.

147
00:09:06,974 --> 00:09:18,435
The better, and you're moving more people through and you're giving the audience who's watching this line move really quickly chances to say yes to, I do want to get into this experience, I'm not going to be in line for 45 minutes, and I will have a good time coming out of it.

148
00:09:20,359 --> 00:09:25,724
Yeah, so another phenomenon we've seen with these experiences is that sometimes people have a bad time in virtual reality.

149
00:09:25,945 --> 00:09:28,247
Sometimes they're not comfortable standing for a long period of time.

150
00:09:28,648 --> 00:09:31,531
Sometimes they get motion sick, or sometimes there's just a technical malfunction.

151
00:09:31,891 --> 00:09:33,053
Those things, it just happens.

152
00:09:33,653 --> 00:09:38,519
The interesting phenomenon has been that no one tells us until after the demo is over.

153
00:09:39,039 --> 00:09:40,199
We say, oh, how was it?

154
00:09:40,219 --> 00:09:41,880
They're like, oh, it's horrible.

155
00:09:41,900 --> 00:09:42,780
I got super sick.

156
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:44,101
We're like, why didn't you tell us?

157
00:09:44,141 --> 00:09:47,042
And there's something about putting on the virtual reality

158
00:09:47,062 --> 00:09:48,262
headset and stepping into that world

159
00:09:48,702 --> 00:09:51,723
that I think people are less likely to complain or just opt

160
00:09:51,803 --> 00:09:51,903
out.

161
00:09:52,343 --> 00:09:54,784
So if you have a nice, short, concise demo,

162
00:09:55,324 --> 00:09:57,465
you're minimizing how long a bad experience is.

163
00:09:58,005 --> 00:09:59,505
And people who really enjoy the experience are saying,

164
00:09:59,525 --> 00:09:59,885
hey, you know what?

165
00:10:00,266 --> 00:10:00,686
No sweat.

166
00:10:00,826 --> 00:10:01,366
Glad you enjoyed it.

167
00:10:01,526 --> 00:10:02,806
You can get back in line and do it again.

168
00:10:02,826 --> 00:10:04,807
There's sort of just an interesting phenomenon

169
00:10:04,847 --> 00:10:05,287
about people.

170
00:10:05,887 --> 00:10:08,888
Just not complaining. I mean, it's cool that people love virtual reality.

171
00:10:08,908 --> 00:10:11,029
There's so much like, yeah, I got to try it. Totally suck.

172
00:10:11,049 --> 00:10:12,490
But, you know, I got to try it.

173
00:10:13,070 --> 00:10:14,991
So, again, keep your experiences short.

174
00:10:17,512 --> 00:10:19,513
Another way to make sure that as many people are going to enjoy

175
00:10:19,553 --> 00:10:21,914
your experience as possible is by designing for inclusivity.

176
00:10:22,314 --> 00:10:25,575
One of the easiest things that you can do to make your experience

177
00:10:25,675 --> 00:10:28,657
broadly accessible is by implementing ambidextrous controls,

178
00:10:29,137 --> 00:10:32,738
just by making it so that a person only has to have the use of one hand to

179
00:10:33,542 --> 00:10:37,086
Like, explore the full functionality and creativity of your app

180
00:10:37,466 --> 00:10:40,209
means that you're opening it up to a broader swath of people.

181
00:10:40,510 --> 00:10:43,533
You also want to consider players of multiple sizes and heights.

182
00:10:44,073 --> 00:10:47,237
You want to make sure that you're not balancing the game for somebody who's very short

183
00:10:47,317 --> 00:10:49,159
and then tall people will be left with no cover

184
00:10:49,579 --> 00:10:51,661
or somebody who's really tall can just look over everything.

185
00:10:51,701 --> 00:10:54,765
We have a... we actually have a co-worker who's incredibly tall

186
00:10:54,825 --> 00:10:55,726
and will sometimes just go...

187
00:10:57,430 --> 00:11:01,271
and then just get you. And it's like, okay, that has to be balanced for player height so that

188
00:11:01,731 --> 00:11:05,833
everybody is on a more even playing field and it's accessible for folks of different sizes and heights.

189
00:11:07,153 --> 00:11:12,075
Another easy, easy win is standing and seated play options. Making this available to people

190
00:11:12,195 --> 00:11:17,417
will encourage others to opt into your experience at show floors, particularly if you're tired,

191
00:11:17,477 --> 00:11:20,418
it's the end of the day, you just want to sit down, but you still want to see the thing,

192
00:11:20,758 --> 00:11:23,939
but maybe you don't feel like ducking and jumping and like turning around a bunch of times,

193
00:11:24,439 --> 00:11:25,539
make seated play an option.

194
00:11:26,300 --> 00:11:28,700
And then of course, swipe to turn is an alternative to room scale.

195
00:11:28,740 --> 00:11:30,961
It's important, particularly if you have seated play,

196
00:11:31,281 --> 00:11:33,302
because then you are not forcing people to do this

197
00:11:35,102 --> 00:11:36,463
multiple times during gameplay.

198
00:11:36,603 --> 00:11:39,363
And that is a really painful maneuver to do with a sore back

199
00:11:39,403 --> 00:11:41,684
from loading in and out show floor events.

200
00:11:41,864 --> 00:11:43,785
And also if you have any spinal column trauma.

201
00:11:46,614 --> 00:11:49,697
So another favorite accessibility feature of ours is reach assist.

202
00:11:50,318 --> 00:11:54,101
So, uh, what we implemented in Jar Wars and have since taken to our other

203
00:11:54,121 --> 00:11:58,266
experiences is that we don't make the player move within arm's reach to grab

204
00:11:58,306 --> 00:11:58,566
something.

205
00:11:58,946 --> 00:12:02,249
Basically if you can see it and you hold your hand out towards it and you press a

206
00:12:02,269 --> 00:12:03,691
grab button, you're going to grab the object.

207
00:12:04,237 --> 00:12:08,503
And we do that in the fiction of Jar Wars, where you have an extendo, like Inspector Gadget,

208
00:12:08,543 --> 00:12:10,806
robotic arm that zooms out and grabs something and pulls it back.

209
00:12:10,826 --> 00:12:13,269
But it has tons of great side effects.

210
00:12:13,430 --> 00:12:15,793
Players aren't busy fiddling with movement,

211
00:12:15,813 --> 00:12:18,176
trying to get close enough to something, but not too close.

212
00:12:19,297 --> 00:12:22,819
Also, as a developer, I appreciate it because I don't have to actually bend down all the way over

213
00:12:23,159 --> 00:12:26,120
to pick up physics objects off the floor in virtual reality all the time.

214
00:12:27,141 --> 00:12:30,542
And it's very intuitive for players. Players understand, they hold their hand towards something,

215
00:12:30,802 --> 00:12:34,404
it lights up, they're going to grab it. And there's lots of ways to explain that in your fiction.

216
00:12:34,464 --> 00:12:38,345
It could be, you know, like Magneto from X-Men, or The Force in Star Wars,

217
00:12:38,445 --> 00:12:42,227
or Akio Broom from Harry Potter. And so, whatever type of experience you're creating,

218
00:12:42,667 --> 00:12:45,888
you can explain it. And we find if it's an app, like not a game, but just an app,

219
00:12:46,369 --> 00:12:48,971
People get it. I'm aiming at something, I click on it, I get it.

220
00:12:49,111 --> 00:12:51,734
And it just works. It doesn't take a ton of explanation.

221
00:12:51,854 --> 00:12:55,838
Consumers understand it when you're trying to make it easier for them to use your app

222
00:12:55,918 --> 00:12:57,439
