00:26:03,770 --> 00:26:06,093
If somebody has an emergency come up that they can leave

445
00:26:06,153 --> 00:26:09,718
and it won't just, it won't hinder the entire demo.

446
00:26:10,539 --> 00:26:12,560
Another thing that you want to do is rotate the roles.

447
00:26:12,701 --> 00:26:16,604
If you have many different staffing areas like squire, line management,

448
00:26:16,984 --> 00:26:18,926
someone to drive the spectator PC view,

449
00:26:19,346 --> 00:26:23,970
you want to rotate people in so that they're not completely burned out on one role.

450
00:26:24,070 --> 00:26:28,994
Because it's a lot of energy and effort of people communication to do line management,

451
00:26:29,374 --> 00:26:31,216
it's a little bit less intense to do squire.

452
00:26:31,576 --> 00:26:36,760
It's even less intense to do the spectator PC, but there are more different types of decisions to make in that position.

453
00:26:36,780 --> 00:26:40,103
So you want to rotate people into roles that they click with and also give them breaks.

454
00:26:40,783 --> 00:26:44,586
Lots of water bottles as well is very important and also standing comfort aids.

455
00:26:44,686 --> 00:26:46,348
So like insoles, pads.

456
00:26:46,768 --> 00:26:50,711
We've all been in a conference for several hours and felt what it feels like to have your...

457
00:26:50,931 --> 00:26:54,574
Basically your heels are liquefying the whole time and it just becomes pain at the end of the day.

458
00:26:54,914 --> 00:26:56,215
You want to protect your staff from this.

459
00:26:56,796 --> 00:26:58,397
And then you also want to keep them informed.

460
00:26:58,797 --> 00:27:01,799
We do that with a document that we call the run of show document,

461
00:27:02,160 --> 00:27:03,981
which has all of the information. It's hefty.

462
00:27:04,001 --> 00:27:06,243
There's an online version and then there's a couple of physical versions

463
00:27:06,403 --> 00:27:08,044
at the place in case the internet goes down.

464
00:27:08,704 --> 00:27:10,586
And this is a theme. That's right.

465
00:27:11,707 --> 00:27:15,650
And it has all the information and emergency contact numbers and protocols

466
00:27:15,770 --> 00:27:17,811
and even some light troubleshooting for the squires

467
00:27:17,931 --> 00:27:19,993
if somebody has to leave and step away for a second.

468
00:27:20,653 --> 00:27:22,555
Yeah. Super, super valuable.

469
00:27:24,816 --> 00:27:31,403
And then, you know, something that we've been working on more the last couple years is what do we do after the demonstration, right?

470
00:27:31,883 --> 00:27:35,547
If you're very focused on turnaround time and trying to get as many people through the experience as possible,

471
00:27:35,947 --> 00:27:39,831
it's easy to be like, hey, thanks a whole lot, you know, take the VR gear off, get out of here.

472
00:27:40,731 --> 00:27:43,874
So lately what we've been doing is almost like a receiving station when someone leaves.

473
00:27:43,934 --> 00:27:46,857
So sometimes there's swag, it could be stickers, posters, or T-shirts.

474
00:27:47,878 --> 00:27:55,541
A couple setups we've done have had automated photos and videos where you can give people a digital memento of their experience.

475
00:27:56,701 --> 00:28:02,223
And also we learned to tell people what the hashtag is because often, again, this is going to go live on the internet forever.

476
00:28:02,603 --> 00:28:05,484
And we want to be able to find the content that people are posting about the experience.

477
00:28:05,504 --> 00:28:09,286
So telling them, hey, this is the official hashtag of this event or this game has really helped.

478
00:28:10,602 --> 00:28:17,052
Something else that we've seen is that high score boards have this really interesting sort of viral element to them,

479
00:28:17,092 --> 00:28:22,240
just like a classic arcade game, where some players are going to play the game or play the experience and enjoy it and be like,

480
00:28:22,260 --> 00:28:25,284
okay, that was cool. And then other people are going to leave and say, well, how did I do?

481
00:28:26,005 --> 00:28:29,669
And so for those players to have a high scoreboard that's posted on a side screen

482
00:28:31,171 --> 00:28:33,474
can really be a win, because they might want to come back and just,

483
00:28:33,514 --> 00:28:35,436
well, can I do better? Can I get a better score?

484
00:28:35,976 --> 00:28:38,719
Or, you know, also very likely they're going to go recruit their friends and say,

485
00:28:38,759 --> 00:28:41,302
hey, here's my score. You should come back and try to beat this one.

486
00:28:41,322 --> 00:28:45,187
So so we're pulling in these old ideas of classic arcade games,

487
00:28:45,747 --> 00:28:46,588
making them new again with VR.

488
00:28:48,355 --> 00:28:50,756
And then of course, you want to have your mailing list again.

489
00:28:50,876 --> 00:28:53,197
If somebody didn't opt in before they knew what the experience was,

490
00:28:53,297 --> 00:28:54,558
maybe now that they've played it, they're like,

491
00:28:54,618 --> 00:28:56,559
no, I definitely want to know when this hits the market.

492
00:28:56,579 --> 00:28:58,620
I've got four buddies I want to play with. I'm ready.

493
00:28:59,040 --> 00:29:00,861
And so you want to have that available for them.

494
00:29:01,021 --> 00:29:04,062
And you want to make that very low friction to just be like, OK, yes.

495
00:29:04,242 --> 00:29:05,403
Email me all of the things.

496
00:29:05,883 --> 00:29:07,664
Make this easy for me to wishlist it.

497
00:29:08,025 --> 00:29:09,325
And then follow up interviews again.

498
00:29:09,546 --> 00:29:12,128
You want to have somebody that's there to answer questions like,

499
00:29:12,348 --> 00:29:13,629
Hey, when can I play this again?

500
00:29:13,689 --> 00:29:14,649
Where are you showing next?

501
00:29:14,729 --> 00:29:18,352
And sometimes we have that answer and that information for some of our installs.

502
00:29:18,392 --> 00:29:20,374
And we're like, yes, you can see us here.

503
00:29:20,674 --> 00:29:24,877
And sometimes it's just like, no, the best way to do this is to follow us on social media to connect with us.

504
00:29:25,057 --> 00:29:26,898
And you just want to build that web of interconnectivity.

505
00:29:28,980 --> 00:29:30,481
Last but not least, safety.

506
00:29:31,907 --> 00:29:35,268
When you're doing any event, you're creating a micro-community.

507
00:29:35,749 --> 00:29:39,851
And frequently when you create a micro-community, you've created the potential for a longer-lasting,

508
00:29:40,011 --> 00:29:40,911
evergreen community.

509
00:29:41,512 --> 00:29:45,354
Any community, any group of people brought together by common likes, passions, goals,

510
00:29:45,394 --> 00:29:51,057
and drives needs a rule of interaction and a base of responsibility and behavior that's

511
00:29:51,097 --> 00:29:51,577
acceptable.

512
00:29:52,037 --> 00:29:56,620
Codes of conduct are the way to pave that way forward and make sure that the community

513
00:29:56,660 --> 00:29:58,501
that you are growing, the event that you are nurturing,

514
00:29:58,981 --> 00:30:03,684
It is supported and kept safe and that it's clear to everybody what's acceptable and not.

515
00:30:04,845 --> 00:30:07,347
So having one of those from the get-go is really important.

516
00:30:07,527 --> 00:30:11,770
If the event that you're showing at or the showcase that you're part of doesn't have one,

517
00:30:11,850 --> 00:30:16,153
you can still put one together for your team and have everybody basically opt into,

518
00:30:16,313 --> 00:30:19,235
yes, I understand what's expected of me and how to behave.

519
00:30:19,956 --> 00:30:21,476
And I've agreed to it and I've signed it.

520
00:30:21,757 --> 00:30:24,818
So we frequently do that with our events and our showcases as well.

521
00:30:25,479 --> 00:30:28,981
Another important thing to include is the emergency contacts for your staff.

522
00:30:29,361 --> 00:30:31,962
If somebody has an accident or if you need to get a hold of somebody,

523
00:30:32,002 --> 00:30:33,863
that's an important piece of information to have.

524
00:30:34,323 --> 00:30:36,585
You also want to have first aid kits because it's boo-boos.

525
00:30:36,665 --> 00:30:37,425
They do happen.

526
00:30:37,825 --> 00:30:40,367
You're up a ladder, you scrape an elbow, you get a paper cut.

527
00:30:40,727 --> 00:30:44,249
You want to be able to band-aid that and not have that be something that puts a crimp in your style.

528
00:30:44,728 --> 00:30:50,272
And then finally, you want to make sure your staff knows how to react in a particular situation and how to report incidents.

529
00:30:50,772 --> 00:30:55,575
We frequently have sort of like just very beginning orientation setups for our new staff members.

530
00:30:56,036 --> 00:30:58,517
And we'll also do a PSA of like, hey, we want to hear what's up.

531
00:30:58,677 --> 00:31:00,819
We want to hear if there's anything that you have questions about.

532
00:31:00,899 --> 00:31:04,321
If somebody is doing something and it's causing doubt for you, we'd rather hear about it than not.

533
00:31:04,701 --> 00:31:10,145
And then we can help coach that situation, the response, and also just make sure that we're keeping everybody safe and supported.

534
00:31:10,894 --> 00:31:14,476
Absolutely. Just how we said that oftentimes people doing a VR demo don't want to complain.

535
00:31:14,896 --> 00:31:18,058
We've also found that new Squires who are working with us for the first time,

536
00:31:18,438 --> 00:31:21,139
they don't know if they're supposed to complain. You know, we really have to tell them, hey,

537
00:31:21,199 --> 00:31:25,301
this is the type of behavior that's out of bounds. We need to know about it and really model that

538
00:31:25,341 --> 00:31:30,084
for them up front. So that orientation really pays big dividends and it helps foster a healthier

539
00:31:30,124 --> 00:31:30,904
community. Yes.

540
00:31:33,966 --> 00:31:36,287
All right. We've got some key takeaways from you to.

541
00:31:38,070 --> 00:31:38,991
Do you want to take this one?

542
00:31:39,011 --> 00:31:42,691
Sure. Yeah. I mean, my big takeaway is I'm a lifelong software developer.

543
00:31:43,351 --> 00:31:46,132
And since I've been working in VR five, six years now,

544
00:31:46,772 --> 00:31:49,593
I've just done an increasing amount of event work and community work.

545
00:31:49,633 --> 00:31:52,593
So if you're in virtual reality and you're making or selling VR,

546
00:31:53,154 --> 00:31:54,434
get ready to show it off a whole lot.

547
00:31:54,874 --> 00:31:56,574
Think about and take events very seriously.

548
00:31:57,755 --> 00:32:01,595
Also, a big shift, a mental shift is you're no longer designing

549
00:32:01,655 --> 00:32:04,036
for this one theoretical player who's going to play the game.

550
00:32:04,892 --> 00:32:06,313
by themselves, at home, alone.

551
00:32:06,614 --> 00:32:09,096
You're designing for this entire demonstration experience.

552
00:32:09,436 --> 00:32:13,200
And I think that these lessons are very applicable to other elements in the game industry going on,

553
00:32:13,220 --> 00:32:16,103
like Twitch streaming, Let's Play videos.

554
00:32:16,503 --> 00:32:19,126
You know, video games are a spectator sport.

555
00:32:19,186 --> 00:32:21,388
VR and AR are absolutely a spectator sport as well.

556
00:32:22,860 --> 00:32:25,041
And when you're at an event, be flexible.

557
00:32:25,761 --> 00:32:26,561
Shit goes wrong.

558
00:32:26,881 --> 00:32:27,502
Shit breaks.

559
00:32:27,882 --> 00:32:28,302
Roll with it.

560
00:32:28,362 --> 00:32:29,583
It hits the fan.

561
00:32:29,663 --> 00:32:30,323
It does occasionally.

562
00:32:30,343 --> 00:32:31,003
Also hit the fan.

563
00:32:31,483 --> 00:32:33,004
So yeah, just roll with it.

564
00:32:33,564 --> 00:32:34,605
Know that that will happen.

565
00:32:34,805 --> 00:32:40,547
Try to arrive early and, you know, have a backup plan.

566
00:32:41,759 --> 00:32:46,501
Speaking of backup plan, always bring your own gear and bring extras. Again, never trust the

567
00:32:46,541 --> 00:32:49,642
internet. You want to make sure that you are bringing all of the things that will allow you

568
00:32:49,662 --> 00:32:53,544
to be as self-reliant as possible, and then bring extra. Because if something does go wrong,

569
00:32:53,624 --> 00:32:57,386
or something extra goes wrong, you want to have some contingency set aside for that.

570
00:32:57,946 --> 00:33:02,589
And if the heavens align, and the sun like cones through the clouds, and it's just a beautiful

571
00:33:02,629 --> 00:33:07,671
choir chorus that hits this perfect note, and nothing goes wrong with your demo on this day,

572
00:33:08,372 --> 00:33:11,493
Your neighbor will have technical issues and one of their adapters won't work

573
00:33:11,553 --> 00:33:13,834
and their headset will have cracked because a player dropped it.

574
00:33:14,214 --> 00:33:15,195
And you'll be able to be like,

575
00:33:15,235 --> 00:33:17,075
Dear friend, I will assist you.

576
00:33:17,976 --> 00:33:21,637
But this community and this creatorship is still new enough

577
00:33:21,717 --> 00:33:25,039
that every first experience that somebody has sort of colors

578
00:33:25,459 --> 00:33:28,680
the entire playing field, even if the experiences are very different.

579
00:33:28,960 --> 00:33:31,522
So if I have a bad first experience in somebody else's VR setup

580
00:33:31,542 --> 00:33:33,863
because the base station was wobbly or not tracking properly,

581
00:33:34,223 --> 00:33:36,624
I'm not necessarily going to get into the next person's VR.

582
00:33:36,724 --> 00:33:37,004
And now.

583
00:33:37,484 --> 00:33:42,768
You've lost that potential customer who would have been wowed and talked to their 30,000 online followers.

584
00:33:42,948 --> 00:33:46,691
So you want to make sure that you're making it as easy as possible for people to have a good time,

585
00:33:47,072 --> 00:33:50,674
not just in your experiences, but in everybody's experiences, because this is a team effort.

586
00:33:51,735 --> 00:33:54,998
Part of that is also cleaning your gear often and in front of the audience, like we said before,

587
00:33:55,398 --> 00:33:59,561
you want to remove barriers to saying yes. And part of that is when you're in a group of people,

588
00:33:59,601 --> 00:34:03,864
you're like, but who here is patient zero? And you want to make sure that you are not

589
00:34:03,924 --> 00:34:05,606
contributing to the zombie apocalypse.

590
00:34:06,046 --> 00:34:06,526
It's important.

591
00:34:06,766 --> 00:34:08,046
And then finally, code of conduct.

592
00:34:08,246 --> 00:34:10,107
Even in a zombie apocalypse, we will need one.

593
00:34:10,307 --> 00:34:11,067
You will need one.

594
00:34:11,567 --> 00:34:16,068
Any VR meetup, any XR party, any AR showcase, any MR event.

595
00:34:17,168 --> 00:34:19,248
Get on it and make sure that you are clearly

596
00:34:19,348 --> 00:34:21,569
stating what's acceptable, what the outcomes

597
00:34:21,609 --> 00:34:23,749
of different behaviors are, and how to keep people

598
00:34:23,789 --> 00:34:24,469
safe and supported.

599
00:34:25,650 --> 00:34:26,050
Well put.

